Description: Glazed composition fitting (?) in the form of the head of an Egyptian woman or goddess (?), maybe for amuletic figure; wearing short wig marked in squares which radiate out in sections from point at top of head, marked by a circle with a dot in the middle (maybe something fixed there, headdress?); wig cut in steeply at the lower back of head, flat surface with segments of wig indicated only by vertical dashes, as if not going to be seen. Below, the neck is shaped as a peg-shaped cone with a ridge above it, diminishing in size to the bottom where there is a hole pierced in the middle. Finely modelled features with precisely incised details, ears without earrings, slanting eyes and eyebrows, small neatly shaped nose and mouth, with small perforations pierced at each end. Glaze surface all gone; yellow core of fine hard texture; very eroded surface, neck chipped.
Bibliographic references: Gardner 1888 / Naukratis II (pl. XIX, no. 5) (Drawing not completely accurate)
Villing et al 2013-2015 / Naukratis: Greeks in Egypt (OK.195) (phase 3)
